I believe is a good approach to use rxjs/forkJoin for handling multiple parallel requests.

[ForkJoin][1] accepts an array of observables as its first argument and returns an observable that emits once all of its passed in observables have completed.

I have refactor your code to something easier to read and that takes advantage of forkJoin to handle departaments and secteurs in parallel so then outputs an array of each resulting data.

If the amount of data you are working on is quite big i would even suggest taking a look into [WebWorkers][2] so its possible to split cpu intensive operations in multiple threads and avoid blocking the main thread.

````
    // map array of departments into an array of Observables
    const departmentsRequests = this.departementGet.map((departement) =&gt; {
        return this.annnonceService.getAnnonces(&#39;departement&#39;, departement);
    });

    const secteurActiviteRequests = this.secteurActGet.map((secteur) =&gt; {
        return this.annnonceService.getAnnonces(&#39;secteurActivite&#39;, secteur);
    });

    // forkJoin takes all Observables and emits once to its subscription
    this.annoncesSubscription = forkJoin([
        forkJoin(departmentsRequests),
        forkJoin(secteurActiviteRequests),
    ]).subscribe(([departaments, secteurs]) =&gt; {
        this.isFetchingData = false;

        // all data has been loaded in parallel from firestore, handle it here
    });

````

  [1]: https://www.learnrxjs.io/operators/combination/forkjoin.html
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_Workers_API/Using_web_workers

