The best option is to keep all the gui in the main application, but since this is not always an option, read further.

First i want to mention the reason why that happens, so that is because the `GUILib/GeneratedFiles` (or whatever the path where Qt tools are configured to put the files generated by `uic`) is not in the `INCLUDEPATH` of MyApp, a quick hack would be to add that path to `INCLUDEPATH`, but that will further complicate stuff like if you want to deploy your library, you&#39;ll need to make sure that the tools are configured to create the files in the same path on all platforms, so not recommended solution.

A much better solution is to create a class that wraps the dialog using [PIMPL][1], and basically from all the external sources you only include the header/s that contain the PIMPL &quot;interface&quot;.

NOTE: With `QObject` the parent is responsible to delete it&#39;s children, so to avoid double-delete don&#39;t use `std::unique_ptr` in case you set a parent to your dialog.

LE:
Or a 3&#39;rd option (actually this is just PIMPL, so technically it&#39;s still second option) would be to avoid the include of the generated file (ui_somedialog.h) into the somedialog.h (the header that you include where you use your library), see the documentation [here][2] on how you can use the uic generated code into C++ code (look at `Using a Pointer Member Variable`).

*//somedialog.h*

    #include &lt;QWidget&gt;
    //notice there is no include for ui_somedialog.h
    namespace Ui {
    // forward reference for the generated class
        class SomeDialog;
    }
    
    class SomeDialog : public QWidget
    ~SomeDialog();
    //...
    private:
    //member pointer to the generated class
        Ui::SomeDialog* ui;
    }

*//somedialog.cpp*

    #include &quot;somedialog.h&quot;
    //here we have the include for ui_somedialog.h
    #include &quot;ui_somedialog.h&quot;

    SomeDialog::SomeDialog(QWidget *parent) :
    QWidget(parent), ui(new Ui::SomeDialog)
    {
        ui-&gt;setupUi(this);
    }

    SomeDialog::~SomeDialog()
    {
        delete ui;
    }

This is a PIMPL-like approach, you only forward-reference the internal class and export an interface to it.

There was a way to set which approach you wanted Qt tools to generate the code for you, but i can&#39;t find it right now, for me the current tools always seem to use this member pointer approach.

  [1]: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/pimpl
  [2]: https://doc.qt.io/qt-5/designer-using-a-ui-file.html#the-single-inheritance-approach

